Also, in such a ruler as Claudius, personal vanity, and the desire to out-do his pre· decessore, must count for something. Suetonius, as might be expected, thinks his desire to win the full honours oi a triumph a sufficient expla- nation ol the whole undertaking²; and the monotony with which the rhetorical boast, that he had been first to extend the empire beyond the Ocean, is paraded in his own speech ³, in the triumphal inscription ⁴, aud in contemporary epigrama ⁸, shows the light in which he wished the achievement to be regarded. Lastly, the prominence ol Narcissus in the narrative oi the despatch of the expedition⁶ suggests the cupidity oi freedmen and other courtiers as another great prompting motivel, and that the increased trade may have led the Romans to exaggerate the mineral and other wealth ol Britain no less than they had before de· preciated it ⁸.
